<subSubSection id="19C96549FF916C5DF9963936181AFB96" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="516C36C2FF916C5DF9963936181AFB96" blockId="29.[151,1437,654,2013]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF916C5DF99639361C68FCD3" bold="true" box="[199,322,798,824]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Glabella inflated and subspherical with sculpture of dense granules; fixigena with small number of large, low tubercles in smaller specimens; all specimens with genal spine, length reduced through ontogeny but still a robust, thorn-like spine in largest specimen; S1 does not fully isolate L1; librigena with broad lateral border, very shallow or obsolete lateral border furrow, and dense granular sculpture on all surfaces, including position of border furrow; pygidium of three segments; pygidial axis with three axial rings but no terminal piece; each pygidial axial ring with transverse row of small tubercles; adaxial pleural region of all three pygidial spines with independently swollen anterior and posterior pleural bands separated by oblique, posterolaterally running, pleural furrow; distal parts of spines nearly flat, with gentle dorsal concavity; distal spines with central row of small tubercles, curved to match posterior curvature of spine, more prominent in smaller specimens; spine tips positioned at posterior margin of spines, acutely angled but blunt; apart from tubercle rows, dorsal pygidial sculpture of dense granules.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="19C96549FF916C5EF9963EAE1E6FF89A" lastPageId="30" lastPageNumber="31" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="516C36C2FF916C5DF9963EAE191FFA92" blockId="29.[151,1437,654,2013]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF916C5DF9963EAE1C66FB4B" bold="true" box="[199,332,1158,1184]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Discussion.</emphasis>
It would be best to compare the morphology of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF916C5DFAD33EAF199BFB4A" authorityName="Adrain &amp; Pérez-Peris" authorityYear="2021" box="[898,1201,1159,1185]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Newfoundlandops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="karimae">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF916C5DFAD33EAF199BFB4A" box="[898,1201,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Newfoundlandops karimae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to that of the oldest known, contemporaneous, species of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF916C5DFB133E831FC0FB2E" authorityName="Beyrich" authorityYear="1845" box="[578,746,1195,1221]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF916C5DFB133E831FC0FB2E" box="[578,746,1195,1221]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This not possible in detail, as those Darriwilian species are based on internal molds of relatively poorly preserved specimens, illustrated with tiny photographs. Instead, the most useful comparisons are with slightly younger, Sandbian, species known from silicified material. In particular, we will focus on 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF916C5DF8093F3F1E27FADA" authority="Whittington and Evitt, 1954" authorityName="Whittington and Evitt" authorityYear="1954" box="[344,781,1302,1329]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pulcher">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF916C5DF8093F3F1CE0FADA" box="[344,458,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">S. pulcher</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF916C5DF8813F3F1E27FADA" author="Whittington, H. B. &amp; Evitt, W. R." box="[464,781,1302,1329]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="1 - 137" refId="ref39275" refString="Whittington, H. B. &amp; Evitt, W. R. (1954) Silicified Middle Ordovician trilobites. Geological Society of America Memoir, 59, 1 - 137." type="journal article" year="1954">Whittington and Evitt, 1954</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, from the Edinburg Formation, 
<collectingRegion id="9317F820FF916C5DFD3E3F3F19E7FADA" box="[1135,1229,1303,1329]" country="United States of America" name="Virginia" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Virginia</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="29C47652FF916C5DFD893F3F1839FADA" box="[1240,1299,1303,1329]" name="United States of America" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">USA</collectingCountry>
, 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF916C5DFC4F3F3F1CD3FABE" authority="Whittington and Evit, 1954" authorityName="Whittington and Evit" authorityYear="1954" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hapsidotus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF916C5DFC4F3F3F1D92FABF" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">S. hapsidotus</emphasis>
Whittington and Evit, 1954
</taxonomicName>
, from the Lincolnshire Formation, 
<collectingRegion id="9317F820FF916C5DFAD83F131ECDFABE" box="[905,999,1339,1365]" country="United States of America" name="Virginia" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Virginia</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="29C47652FF916C5DFAA23F131904FABE" box="[1011,1070,1339,1365]" name="United States of America" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">USA</collectingCountry>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF916C5DFD3A3F131C7CFA92" authority="Chatterton and Ludvigsen, 1976" authorityName="Chatterton and Ludvigsen" authorityYear="1976" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arenosus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF916C5DFD3A3F1319C7FABF" box="[1131,1261,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">S. arenosus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF916C5DFDA43F131C7CFA92" author="Chatterton, B. D. E. &amp; Ludvigsen, R." pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="1 - 106" refId="ref35563" refString="Chatterton, B. D. E. &amp; Ludvigsen, R. (1976) Silicified Middle Ordovician trilobites from the South Nahanni River area, District of Mackenzie, Canada. Palaeontographica, Abteilung A, 154, 1 - 106." type="journal article" year="1976">Chatterton and Ludvigsen, 1976</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, from the Esbataottine Formation, 
<collectingRegion id="9317F820FF916C5DFB8D3F771EE4FA92" box="[732,974,1375,1401]" country="Canada" name="Northwest Territories" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Northwest Territories</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="29C47652FF916C5DFA883F77191BFA92" box="[985,1073,1375,1401]" name="Canada" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Canada</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="516C36C2FF916C5DF9963FAB1E58F8EE" blockId="29.[151,1437,654,2013]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
In cranidial morphology, 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF916C5DF8B73FAB1F4EFA76" authorityName="Adrain &amp; Pérez-Peris" authorityYear="2021" box="[486,612,1411,1437]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Newfoundlandops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="karimae">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF916C5DF8B73FAB1F4EFA76" box="[486,612,1411,1437]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">N. karimae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems very close to these three species. All of the species share inflated, nearly spherical glabellae, small fixigenae, and genal spines of the same relative lengths. They share nearly identical dimensions in dorsal view. They share a pervasive sculpture of dense granulation on all dorsal surfaces. There are only two substantive differences. Species of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF916C5DFBE23FC71E71F9E2" authorityName="Beyrich" authorityYear="1845" box="[691,859,1519,1545]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF916C5DFBE23FC71E71F9E2" box="[691,859,1519,1545]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have S 
<quantity id="962B9B27FF916C5DFAE03FC71EF3F9E2" box="[945,985,1519,1545]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" unit="in" value="1.0">1 in</quantity>
posterior contact (if sometimes weakly) with the occipital furrow to completely isolate L1. In 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF916C5DFBA33C3B1E45F9C6" authorityName="Adrain &amp; Pérez-Peris" authorityYear="2021" box="[754,879,1555,1581]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Newfoundlandops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="karimae">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF916C5DFBA33C3B1E45F9C6" box="[754,879,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">N. karimae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a faint furrow seems present posteriorly in small specimens (Pl. 11, fig. 16) and certainly L1 is independently inflated from the median glabellar lobe, but in larger specimens (Pl. 11, figs 1, 4) S1 clearly terminates about a third of the distance of L1 posteriorly. Secondly, the fixigena of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF916C5DF9A13C571C47F972" authorityName="Adrain &amp; Pérez-Peris" authorityYear="2021" box="[240,365,1663,1689]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Newfoundlandops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="karimae">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF916C5DF9A13C571C47F972" box="[240,365,1663,1689]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">N. karimae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
retains a small number of low tubercles, and there are tiny tubercles also on the posterior border and genal spine (Pl. 11, figs 11, 12, 16, 25). However, the fixigenal tubercles are actually themselves covered in granules. They are more evident in smaller specimens. Apart from these two features, the cranidium of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF916C5DFC713CEF18B6F90A" authorityName="Adrain &amp; Pérez-Peris" authorityYear="2021" box="[1312,1436,1735,1761]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Newfoundlandops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="karimae">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF916C5DFC713CEF18B6F90A" box="[1312,1436,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">N. karimae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is more or less identical with those of the 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF916C5DFB3A3CC31E58F8EE" box="[619,882,1771,1797]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF916C5DFB3A3CC31E39F8EE" box="[619,787,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
species.
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="516C36C2FF916C5EF9963D2718BDFD8A" blockId="29.[151,1437,654,2013]" lastBlockId="30.[151,1437,151,1905]" lastPageId="30" lastPageNumber="31" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
The librigena share with those of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF916C5DFB193D271FDAF8C2" authorityName="Beyrich" authorityYear="1845" box="[584,752,1807,1833]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF916C5DFB193D271FDAF8C2" box="[584,752,1807,1833]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
pervasive granular sculpture on the lateral border and field, similar to that covering the cranidium in both genera. The presence of dense granular sculpture on the librigenal field seems to be uniquely shared within all of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF916C5DFBE03D7F1E13F89A" authorityName="Hawle and Corda" authorityYear="1847" box="[689,825,1879,1905]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Cheiruridae</taxonomicName>
. The eye of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF916C5DFA963D7F196FF89A" authorityName="Adrain &amp; Pérez-Peris" authorityYear="2021" box="[967,1093,1879,1905]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Newfoundlandops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="karimae">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF916C5DFA963D7F196FF89A" box="[967,1093,1879,1905]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">N. karimae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very small, with prominent lenses (Pl. 11, fig. 17). It is nearly identical in size, lens number, and prominence with that of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF916C5DFDC93D53183DF87F" authorityName="Chatterton and Ludvigsen" authorityYear="1976" box="[1176,1303,1915,1941]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arenosus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF916C5DFDC93D53183DF87F" box="[1176,1303,1915,1941]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">S. arenosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF916C5DFC753D531CA2F852" author="Chatterton, B. D. E. &amp; Ludvigsen, R." pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="1 - 106" refId="ref35563" refString="Chatterton, B. D. E. &amp; Ludvigsen, R. (1976) Silicified Middle Ordovician trilobites from the South Nahanni River area, District of Mackenzie, Canada. Palaeontographica, Abteilung A, 154, 1 - 106." type="journal article" year="1976">Chatterton and Ludvigsen, 1976</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 13, fig. 46). All of the 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF916C5DFBED3DB71E94F852" box="[700,958,1951,1977]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF916C5DFBED3DB71E4EF852" box="[700,868,1951,1977]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
have librigenae with a broad, deep lateral border furrow about the same width as the remaining field, bounded posteriorly and anteriorly by sutural ridges, and lacking sculpture. While the librigena of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EFBCD3ABF1E30FF5A" authorityName="Adrain &amp; Pérez-Peris" authorityYear="2021" box="[668,794,151,177]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Newfoundlandops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="karimae">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EFBCD3ABF1E30FF5A" box="[668,794,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">N. karimae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lack such a well defined furrow, a depression of similar unusual width is developed in the same position (see especially Pl. 11, fig. 19), across which the granular sculpture runs uninterrupted from the lateral border onto the field. Librigenae of the 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EFA9E3AF719E5FF12" box="[975,1231,223,249]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EFA9E3AF7195DFF12" box="[975,1143,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
differ from that of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EF9C63B2B1C39FEF6" authorityName="Adrain &amp; Pérez-Peris" authorityYear="2021" box="[151,275,259,285]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Newfoundlandops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="karimae">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EF9C63B2B1C39FEF6" box="[151,275,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">N. karimae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in two prominent ways. Some of the derived morphology of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EFAEB3B2B1948FEF6" authorityName="Beyrich" authorityYear="1845" box="[954,1122,259,285]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EFAEB3B2B1948FEF6" box="[954,1122,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems to be associated with enrollment. All species have a deep coaptative furrow on the underside of the posterior part of lateral border such that when seen in internal view (
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF926C5EFB5A3B631E57FE8E" author="Chatterton, B. D. E. &amp; Ludvigsen, R." box="[523,893,331,357]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="1 - 106" refId="ref35563" refString="Chatterton, B. D. E. &amp; Ludvigsen, R. (1976) Silicified Middle Ordovician trilobites from the South Nahanni River area, District of Mackenzie, Canada. Palaeontographica, Abteilung A, 154, 1 - 106." type="journal article" year="1976">Chatterton and Ludvigsen, 1976</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 13, figs 35, 36), the region has a prominent flange jutting backward above the doublure, on the far side of the coaptative furrow. This furrow can be seen in all species of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EF85E3BBB1C9DFE46" authorityName="Beyrich" authorityYear="1845" box="[271,439,403,429]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EF85E3BBB1C9DFE46" box="[271,439,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for which information is available and functioned to receive the pleurae of the first thoracic segment during enrollment (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF926C5EFB123B9F1FD6FE3A" author="Ramskold, L." box="[579,764,439,465]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="175 - 210" refId="ref37978" refString="Ramskold, L. (1983) Silurian cheirurid trilobites from Gotland. Palaeontology, 26, 175 - 210." type="journal article" year="1983">Ramsköld, 1983</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 28, fig. 12a). There is no similar furrow in 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EFDAF3B9F1850FE3A" authorityName="Adrain &amp; Pérez-Peris" authorityYear="2021" box="[1278,1402,439,465]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Newfoundlandops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="karimae">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EFDAF3B9F1850FE3A" box="[1278,1402,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">N. karimae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in which the ventrolateral part of the lateral border remains normally inflated, with no break in morphology from more anterior regions (Pl. 11, fig. 20). Second, the librigenal fields in 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EFA203BD71ED8FDF3" authorityName="Chatterton and Ludvigsen" authorityYear="1976" box="[881,1010,511,537]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arenosus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EFA203BD71ED8FDF3" box="[881,1010,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">S. arenosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF926C5EFD533BD71859FDF2" author="Chatterton, B. D. E. &amp; Ludvigsen, R." box="[1026,1395,511,537]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="1 - 106" refId="ref35563" refString="Chatterton, B. D. E. &amp; Ludvigsen, R. (1976) Silicified Middle Ordovician trilobites from the South Nahanni River area, District of Mackenzie, Canada. Palaeontographica, Abteilung A, 154, 1 - 106." type="journal article" year="1976">Chatterton and Ludvigsen, 1976</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 13, fig. 46) and 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EF816380B1CF1FDD6" authorityName="Whittington and Evit" authorityYear="1954" box="[327,475,547,573]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hapsidotus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EF816380B1CF1FDD6" box="[327,475,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">S. hapsidotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF926C5EF8BA380B1E0FFDD6" author="Whittington, H. B. &amp; Evitt, W. R." box="[491,805,546,573]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="1 - 137" refId="ref39275" refString="Whittington, H. B. &amp; Evitt, W. R. (1954) Silicified Middle Ordovician trilobites. Geological Society of America Memoir, 59, 1 - 137." type="journal article" year="1954">Whittington and Evitt, 1954</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 32, figs 29–31) have prominent caecal pits (that of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EFCD6380B1DC7FD8A" authorityName="Whittington and Evitt" authorityYear="1954" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pulcher">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EFCD6380B1DC7FD8A" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">S. pulcher</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may have, too, but the photographs are too tiny to tell). These are absent from the librigena of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EFC45386F18BBFD8A" authorityName="Adrain &amp; Pérez-Peris" authorityYear="2021" box="[1300,1425,583,609]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Newfoundlandops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="karimae">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EFC45386F18BBFD8A" box="[1300,1425,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">N. karimae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="516C36C2FF926C5EF9963843194CFCD2" blockId="30.[151,1437,151,1905]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
The hypostome of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EF8C638431F38FD6E" authorityName="Adrain &amp; Pérez-Peris" authorityYear="2021" box="[407,530,619,645]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Newfoundlandops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="karimae">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EF8C638431F38FD6E" box="[407,530,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">N. karimae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Pl. 12, fig. 3) is very like those of species of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EFD5A38431999FD6E" authorityName="Beyrich" authorityYear="1845" box="[1035,1203,619,645]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EFD5A38431999FD6E" box="[1035,1203,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Compared with that of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EF9E538A71C19FD43" authorityName="Chatterton and Ludvigsen" authorityYear="1976" box="[180,307,655,681]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arenosus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EF9E538A71C19FD43" box="[180,307,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">S. arenosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF926C5EF81138A71F81FD42" author="Chatterton, B. D. E. &amp; Ludvigsen, R." box="[320,683,655,681]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="1 - 106" refId="ref35563" refString="Chatterton, B. D. E. &amp; Ludvigsen, R. (1976) Silicified Middle Ordovician trilobites from the South Nahanni River area, District of Mackenzie, Canada. Palaeontographica, Abteilung A, 154, 1 - 106." type="journal article" year="1976">Chatterton and Ludvigsen, 1976</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 13, figs 32, 42), there are no substantial differences. The general dimensions are identical, the lateral borders are of the same width, the middle body has the middle furrow in exactly the same position, and the posterior border is bilobate, with a median indentation. The entire ventral surface in both species is covered in dense granular sculpture. The only minor differences are that the hypostome of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EFC5438D318A8FCFE" authorityName="Adrain &amp; Pérez-Peris" authorityYear="2021" box="[1285,1410,763,789]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Newfoundlandops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="karimae">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EFC5438D318A8FCFE" box="[1285,1410,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">N. karimae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is slightly longer relative to its width, and the posterior border lobes are somewhat larger.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="516C36C2FF926C5EF996396B1ED2FBB2" blockId="30.[151,1437,151,1905]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
While the cephala of these taxa share many features, differences in the pygidia are admittedly profound. The cephala are so similar and the pygidia so dissimilar, in fact, that the question of sclerite association in the Table Cove Formation species should be addressed before comparing pygidial morphology. In brief, the cephalic sclerites and pygidia are both reasonably common. There is literally no other cheirurid pygidial 
<typeStatus id="8E688860FF926C5EFD173987195CFC22" box="[1094,1142,943,969]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">type</typeStatus>
that the cephalic sclerites could possibly be associated with, and no other cephalic material that the pygidia could possibly be associated with. Other cheirurids occurring at horizon TCM 18 (
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EFBE539DF1E84FBFA" box="[692,942,1015,1041]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerocoryphe" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="becki">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EFBE539DF1E84FBFA" box="[692,942,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Sphaerocoryphe becki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EFAEC39DF19BEFBFA" baseAuthorityName="Billings" baseAuthorityYear="1865" box="[957,1172,1015,1041]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Laneites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="polydorus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EFAEC39DF19BEFBFA" box="[957,1172,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Laneites polydorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, etc.) have pygidia and other sclerites with well known and expected general morphology. Hence, the association of cephalic material on 
<figureCitation id="C9E82A47FF926C5EF9C63E171DDBFBB2" box="[151,241,1087,1113]" captionStart="PLATE 11" captionStartId="62.[151,234,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-27@62.[151,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="PLATE 11" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5531929" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5531929/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Plate 11</figureCitation>
with the pygidia on 
<figureCitation id="C9E82A47FF926C5EF8893E171F19FBB2" box="[472,563,1087,1113]" captionStart="PLATE 12" captionStartId="64.[151,234,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-27@64.[151,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="PLATE 12" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5531931" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5531931/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Plate 12</figureCitation>
is correct beyond any reasonable doubt.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="516C36C2FF926C5EF9963E4B1F40F956" blockId="30.[151,1437,151,1905]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
All species of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EF83C3E4B1F3FFB96" authorityName="Beyrich" authorityYear="1845" box="[365,533,1123,1149]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EF83C3E4B1F3FFB96" box="[365,533,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
share a pygidium which at least in large adult specimens is highly tagmatized, with robust, club-like spines and often with the third ring and terminal piece fully merged. This morphology is unique to the genus, and is the main reason its affinities are difficult to determine. There are some apparent points of similarity with 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EF8153EE71CEBFB02" authorityName="Adrain &amp; Pérez-Peris" authorityYear="2021" box="[324,449,1231,1257]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Newfoundlandops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="karimae">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EF8153EE71CEBFB02" box="[324,449,1231,1257]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">N. karimae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but not many. All of the taxa have three pygidial segments. The ventral doublure of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EFCD23EE71DD9FAE6" authorityName="Adrain &amp; Pérez-Peris" authorityYear="2021" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Newfoundlandops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="karimae">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EFCD23EE71DD9FAE6" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">N. karimae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species forms a ventral rim, and has a subquadrate median embayment (Pl. 12, figs11, 14). This is a close match for the condition in 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EF8953F3F1F46FADA" authorityName="Beyrich" authorityYear="1845" box="[452,620,1303,1329]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EF8953F3F1F46FADA" box="[452,620,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF926C5EFB2F3F3F1E97FADA" author="Whittington, H. B. &amp; Evitt, W. R." box="[638,957,1302,1329]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="1 - 137" refId="ref39275" refString="Whittington, H. B. &amp; Evitt, W. R. (1954) Silicified Middle Ordovician trilobites. Geological Society of America Memoir, 59, 1 - 137." type="journal article" year="1954">Whittington and Evitt, 1954</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 20, fig. 14; 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF926C5EFD203F3F1DF8FABE" author="Chatterton, B. D. E. &amp; Ludvigsen, R." pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="1 - 106" refId="ref35563" refString="Chatterton, B. D. E. &amp; Ludvigsen, R. (1976) Silicified Middle Ordovician trilobites from the South Nahanni River area, District of Mackenzie, Canada. Palaeontographica, Abteilung A, 154, 1 - 106." type="journal article" year="1976">Chatterton and Ludvigsen, 1976</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 13, figs 23, 28). The differences are many. Early species of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EFAEA3F131949FABE" authorityName="Beyrich" authorityYear="1845" box="[955,1123,1339,1365]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EFAEA3F131949FABE" box="[955,1123,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
do sometimes retain a few tubercles on their axial rings (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF926C5EFB763F771E40FA92" author="Whittington, H. B. &amp; Evitt, W. R." box="[551,874,1374,1401]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="1 - 137" refId="ref39275" refString="Whittington, H. B. &amp; Evitt, W. R. (1954) Silicified Middle Ordovician trilobites. Geological Society of America Memoir, 59, 1 - 137." type="journal article" year="1954">Whittington and Evitt, 1954</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 21, fig. 1), but none have transverse tubercle rows like 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EF8593FAB1CACFA76" authorityName="Adrain &amp; Pérez-Peris" authorityYear="2021" box="[264,390,1411,1437]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Newfoundlandops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="karimae">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EF8593FAB1CACFA76" box="[264,390,1411,1437]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">N. karimae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. All species of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EFB693FAB1FCAFA76" authorityName="Beyrich" authorityYear="1845" box="[568,736,1411,1437]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EFB693FAB1FCAFA76" box="[568,736,1411,1437]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have a terminal piece, although it is often partially or wholly fused with the third axial ring. The pygidium of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EFBFD3F8F1EF2FA2A" authorityName="Adrain &amp; Pérez-Peris" authorityYear="2021" box="[684,984,1447,1473]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Newfoundlandops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="karimae">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EFBFD3F8F1EF2FA2A" box="[684,984,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Newfoundlandops karimae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
definitively lacks a terminal piece. Most obviously, the pygidial spines of 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EFB5B3FE31FACFA0E" authorityName="Adrain &amp; Pérez-Peris" authorityYear="2021" box="[522,646,1483,1509]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Newfoundlandops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="karimae">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EFB5B3FE31FACFA0E" box="[522,646,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">N. karimae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are dorsoventrally flattened, versus inflated, and the distal parts of the pleurae have distinct anterior and posterior pleural bands separated by an obliquely set pleural furrow, similar to that seen in cheirurines. There is no sign of pleural bands or furrows on 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EFAD13C3B1902F9C6" authorityName="Beyrich" authorityYear="1845" box="[896,1064,1555,1581]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EFAD13C3B1902F9C6" box="[896,1064,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
segments. Some Ordovician species do have a shallow furrow more or less bisecting the robust pleural spines (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF926C5EFD613C1F18B2F9BA" author="Chatterton, B. D. E. &amp; Ludvigsen, R." box="[1072,1432,1591,1617]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="1 - 106" refId="ref35563" refString="Chatterton, B. D. E. &amp; Ludvigsen, R. (1976) Silicified Middle Ordovician trilobites from the South Nahanni River area, District of Mackenzie, Canada. Palaeontographica, Abteilung A, 154, 1 - 106." type="journal article" year="1976">Chatterton and Ludvigsen, 1976</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 13, fig. 22), but this develops late in ontogeny and does not seem to be a true pleural furrow. Early ontogenetic pygidia (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation id="35424B33FF926C5EF8653C571F5CF972" author="Whittington, H. B. &amp; Evitt, W. R." box="[308,630,1662,1689]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="1 - 137" refId="ref39275" refString="Whittington, H. B. &amp; Evitt, W. R. (1954) Silicified Middle Ordovician trilobites. Geological Society of America Memoir, 59, 1 - 137." type="journal article" year="1954">Whittington and Evitt, 1954</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 17, figs 39, 43, 49, 50) are subcylindrical in their proximal pleural regions, with no hint of bands or furrows.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="516C36C2FF926C5EF9963CEF1E6FF89A" blockId="30.[151,1437,151,1905]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
In sum, we are equivocal about the possibility of relationship, but consider on the basis of what is known that the positively shared cephalic features outweigh the pygidial differences. 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EFAB53CC319A6F8EE" authorityName="Beyrich" authorityYear="1845" box="[996,1164,1771,1797]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Sphaerexochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EFAB53CC319A6F8EE" box="[996,1164,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Sphaerexochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has to have a cheirurid sister taxon, and whatever it is, that sister taxon lacks the derived thoracopygidial morphology. 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EFD833D2718B6F8C2" authorityName="Adrain &amp; Pérez-Peris" authorityYear="2021" box="[1234,1436,1807,1833]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" genus="Newfoundlandops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63A7EAD0FF926C5EFD833D2718B6F8C2" box="[1234,1436,1807,1833]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Newfoundlandops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is apparently the best candidate known, and so we tentatively assign it to 
<taxonomicName id="96D34D41FF926C5EFA873D1B19B3F8A6" authorityName="Opik" authorityYear="1937" box="[982,1177,1843,1869]" pageId="30" pageNumber="29" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Sphaerexochinae">Sphaerexochinae</taxonomicName>
. More information and discoveries will likely be required to evaluate the hypothesis.
</paragraph>
